source: Here is a (slightly longer than) toot-length crash course in what I mean by dad-ification:
translation: "Dad-ification" is a concept that I coined to describe the ideological transformation of society that my friends and I were observing in the early 2010s. Back then, there was a growing movement to "erase masculinity"--to denigrate, sanitize, and ultimately eradicate all traditionally "masculine" elements from society. This movement found support among liberals, conservatives, and even some parts of the "men's rights" community. But my friends and I saw this as a threat to men, to masculinity, and to our culture as a whole. We argued that masculinity wasn't just some arbitrary set of traits that we inherited from our fathers or grandfathers--it was a vital part of what made us human, and it was worth preserving and celebrating. So we coined the term "dad-ification" to describe a "pro-family, pro-fatherhood, pro-masculinity" movement that would stand up to the "anti-masculinity" brigade and defend traditional masculinity from harm. Today, that movement has grown and evolved in unexpected ways, but the basic concept remains the same--we're still fighting to defend masculinity from those who would erase it, and to promote strong, healthy, happy fathers and families in our society.
